1324","1278–Male":"1278–Deceased","1230–1316":"1230–1316","1235–1312":"1235–1312","before 1312":"before 1312","before 1289":"before 1289","1274":"1274","1230":"1230","1260":"1260","1290":"1290","1316":"1316","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","after 1316":"after 1316","1324":"1324","Abt 1278":"about 1278","1312":"1312","1235":"1235","1257":"1257","Abt 1255":"about 1255","1278":"1278","1255":"1255","1317":"1317","Charlton Mackrell, Somerset, England":"Charlton Mackrell, Somerset, England","Lytes Cary, Charlton Mackrell, Somerset, England, United Kingdom":"Charlton Mackrell, Somerset, England, United Kingdom","Charlton, Somerset, England":"Charlton, Somerset, England","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Lyte","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Light  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Light","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>liht</i> ‘light, active’ (Old English <i>lēoht</i>).","English: topographic name from Middle English <i>liht</i>, <i>leht</i> ‘light’ (Old English <i>lēoht</i>), used for a ‘light place, clearing, glade’.","English: nickname from Middle English <i>lit</i> ‘little’ (Old English <i>lȳt</i>). Compare   Little  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":4,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":35,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":60,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Lyte was born about 1255, in Charlton Mackrell, Somerset, England, his father, William le Lyte, was 26 and his mother, Margery Blomvill, was 21. He married Isabella Draycott in 1274, in Charlton Mackrell, Somerset, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died after 1316, in his hometown, and was buried in England."},"et":{"Abt 1255–after 1316":"umbes 1255–pärast 1316","1255–1316":"1255–1316","1260–Male":"1260–Surnud","1257–1324":"1257–1324","1278–Male":"1278–Surnud","1230–1316":"1230–1316","1235–1312":"1235–1312","before 1312":"enne 1312","before 1289":"enne 1289","1274":"1274","1230":"1230","1260":"1260","1290":"1290","1316":"1316","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","after 1316":"pär